# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SECTION 3 — WorkIQ Calendar MCP (agent365)
# Endpoint: https://agent365.svc.cloud.microsoft/agents/tenants/{tenantId}/servers/mcp_CalendarTools
# Requires a bearer token scoped to the agent365 / WorkIQ Calendar resource.
# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ─── Calendar-specific auth variables ────────────────────────────────────────
# ─── Calendar-specific auth variables ────────────────────────────────────────
# ⚠️ The Azure CLI client (04b07795-…) is NOT preauthorized for
# `McpServers.CalendarTools.All` on the agent365 API (ea9ffc3e-…).
# Requesting that scope with it returns AADSTS65002.
#
# You need a client that IS allowed to ask for the Calendar scope.
# Pick ONE of the two options below.
#
# ─── OPTION A: Register your own app in your tenant ──────────────────────────
# 1. Entra portal → App registrations → New registration
#      Name: e.g. "calendar-mcp-rest-client"
#      Supported account types: Single tenant
#      Redirect URI: (leave blank — device flow doesn't need one)
# 2. Authentication → "Allow public client flows" = YES (required for device code).
# 3. API permissions → Add a permission → APIs my organization uses →
#      search "ea9ffc3e-8a23-4a7d-836d-234d7c7565c1" (or "agent365") →
#      Delegated → McpServers.CalendarTools.All → Add → Grant admin consent.
# 4. Copy the Application (client) ID into @deviceClientId below.
#
# ─── OPTION B: Ask the agent365 team to preauthorize Azure CLI ───────────────
# Have the API owner add 04b07795-8ddb-461a-bbee-02f9e1bf7b46 to the
# `preAuthorizedApplications` list on the agent365 app for the
# McpServers.CalendarTools.All scope. Then OPTION A is not needed.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Client id used for device-code login. Replace with your own app reg (OPTION A)
# or keep 04b07795-... only if OPTION B preauth has been granted.
@deviceClientId  = 54881055-411d-41b2-8f25-f1312a1abfe6

# agent365 resource app id (audience aud=ea9ffc3e-... in the issued token):
@agent365AppId   = ea9ffc3e-8a23-4a7d-836d-234d7c7565c1

# Explicit Calendar scope — DISCOVERED via 3.6 (RFC 9728 metadata).
# The agent365 MCP wants a token whose aud = the full resource URL, not the
# app id. Use the resource URL + "/.default" as the scope.
@calendarResource = https://agent365.svc.cloud.microsoft/agents/tenants/{{tenantId}}/servers/mcp_CalendarTools
@calendarScope    = {{calendarResource}}/.default offline_access openid profile
# Fallbacks (only if AAD returns invalid_scope):
#   {{agent365AppId}}/McpServers.Calendar.All offline_access
#   {{agent365AppId}}/.default

# Paste the access_token from step 3.0b below into this variable.
# ⚠️ CONFIRMED WORKING with a token whose `scp` is `McpServers.Calendar.All`
#    and `aud` is `ea9ffc3e-8a23-4a7d-836d-234d7c7565c1`. If you get 401,
#    99% of the time it's one of these:
#      - You forgot to replace the placeholder below (still says REPLACE_...)
#      - You pasted with a trailing newline or accidental space
#      - You included the literal word "Bearer " before the token
#    Paste ONLY the raw `eyJ...` value on a single line, no quotes.
@calendarBearer  = eyJ0eXAiOiJKV1QiLCJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6IndoMDZzRWt6TEhKNXNOTmFVeVJZMl82TzhLMCJ9..FcE5_ovvTL9ExjDMugBmAAn70sP1dqLWfrF6EFggqHg-trJD3vagsaAHmOKUg_qeuXARutMm2QGnvSMw9UNxdTTZP6Urc7SC2RV-T7VeBXQs-P9gCb1Bplm9UnVGSi98Bl7PkYrIA4T5VAoG0VF-lxlSyPyI3LHYi9nkdygbU1erSzGEDLvhHdw81QuiduilYylllpb0XwuqzVveLbZBMuEAI1G82FWA7Xn9WzRMZPUOnmNIV3aIIm64taZ2E2vualGPdUWow6KmAQTqMyJYvk_XTmP4PrKnws8enjyj6EifFvt7rUM3R4_rzGcZLeOfog0nrBFQTS9oVfeF6BUwQA

### 3.0a Start device-code flow
# Run this, then open the returned `verification_uri` in a browser and enter
# the `user_code`. **You must consent to the Calendar scope on that page.**
# Copy `device_code` is auto-wired into step 3.0b via response variable.
# @name calDeviceCode
POST https://login.microsoftonline.com/{{tenantId}}/oauth2/v2.0/devicecode
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded

client_id={{deviceClientId}}&scope={{calendarScope}}

### 3.0b Poll for the token (run AFTER completing the browser step in 3.0a)
# Auto-uses device_code from 3.0a. After this returns 200, copy `access_token`
# into @calendarBearer above.
# @name calToken
POST https://login.microsoftonline.com/{{tenantId}}/oauth2/v2.0/token
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded

grant_type=urn:ietf:params:oauth:grant-type:device_code&client_id={{deviceClientId}}&device_code={{calDeviceCode.response.body.device_code}}

# Alternative (PowerShell one-liner using Azure CLI):
#   az login --tenant 0c2614e6-a76a-433c-80fd-88ac91e67b9d --use-device-code
#   az account get-access-token --resource ea9ffc3e-8a23-4a7d-836d-234d7c7565c1 --query accessToken -o tsv
# (Note: `az account get-access-token` always requests `.default`, so it will
#  only work if McpServers.CalendarTools.All is already admin-consented for
#  the Azure CLI client. If not, use the device-code flow above which lets
#  you consent interactively.)

### 3.0c Decode current @calendarBearer (sanity check audience + scopes)
# Paste the token at jwt.ms or run locally:
#   PowerShell:  $t = "<token>"; $p = $t.Split('.')[1].PadRight(($t.Split('.')[1].Length + 3) -band -bnot 3, '='); [Text.Encoding]::UTF8.GetString([Convert]::FromBase64String($p.Replace('-','+').Replace('_','/')))
# Confirm: aud == ea9ffc3e-8a23-4a7d-836d-234d7c7565c1 AND scp contains a Calendar entry.

### 3.1 initialize (REQUIRED first call per MCP spec)
# @name calInit
POST {{calendarMcp}}
Accept: {{accept}}
Content-Type: application/json
MCP-Protocol-Version: {{mcpVersion}}
x-anchor-mailbox: {{anchorMailbox}}
Authorization: Bearer {{calendarBearer}}

{
  "jsonrpc": "2.0",
  "id": 1,
  "method": "initialize",
  "params": {
    "protocolVersion": "2025-06-18",
    "capabilities": {},
    "clientInfo": { "name": "rest-client", "version": "0.0.1" }
  }
}

### 3.2 tools/list
POST {{calendarMcp}}
Accept: {{accept}}
Content-Type: application/json
MCP-Protocol-Version: {{mcpVersion}}
x-anchor-mailbox: {{anchorMailbox}}
Authorization: Bearer {{calendarBearer}}

{ "jsonrpc": "2.0", "id": 2, "method": "tools/list" }

### 3.3 resources/list
POST {{calendarMcp}}
Accept: {{accept}}
Content-Type: application/json
MCP-Protocol-Version: {{mcpVersion}}
x-anchor-mailbox: {{anchorMailbox}}
Authorization: Bearer {{calendarBearer}}

{ "jsonrpc": "2.0", "id": 3, "method": "resources/list" }

### 3.4 prompts/list
POST {{calendarMcp}}
Accept: {{accept}}
Content-Type: application/json
MCP-Protocol-Version: {{mcpVersion}}
x-anchor-mailbox: {{anchorMailbox}}
Authorization: Bearer {{calendarBearer}}

{ "jsonrpc": "2.0", "id": 4, "method": "prompts/list" }

### 3.5 401 diagnostic — read the WWW-Authenticate header
# Use this if 3.1 returns 401. Check the response's headers tab for
# `WWW-Authenticate: Bearer error="invalid_token", error_description="..."`
# which states the EXACT reason (bad audience, missing scope, expired, etc.).
OPTIONS {{calendarMcp}}
Authorization: Bearer {{calendarBearer}}

### 3.6 Discover protected-resource metadata (RFC 9728)
# The 401 response pointed here. This document tells you the canonical
# `resource` (= required aud), `scopes_supported`, and `authorization_servers`.
# After running this, update @calendarScope to match `scopes_supported[0]`
# (e.g. "<resource>/McpServers.CalendarTools.All") and re-run 3.0a → 3.0b.
# @name calResourceMeta
GET https://agent365.svc.cloud.microsoft/.well-known/oauth-protected-resource/agents/tenants/{{tenantId}}/servers/mcp_CalendarTools
Accept: application/json

### 3.7 Discover the authorization server's OIDC config
# Use the first entry from `authorization_servers` in 3.6's response.
# Example: https://login.microsoftonline.com/{{tenantId}}/v2.0
GET https://login.microsoftonline.com/{{tenantId}}/v2.0/.well-known/openid-configuration
Accept: application/json

### 3.8 tools/call → CreateEvent (book a meeting with myself)
# Schema confirmed from tools/list. Notes:
#  - `timeZone` uses Windows TZ ids (e.g. "Romance Standard Time" = Paris,
#    "Pacific Standard Time", "UTC"). NOT IANA ids like "Europe/Paris".
#  - `attendeeEmails` is a flat string[] (UPNs or SMTP addresses).
#  - `isOnlineMeeting` defaults to true → server auto-adds a Teams link.
#  - Edit startDateTime / endDateTime to a future time before sending.
POST {{calendarMcp}}
Accept: {{accept}}
Content-Type: application/json
MCP-Protocol-Version: {{mcpVersion}}
x-anchor-mailbox: {{anchorMailbox}}
Authorization: Bearer {{calendarBearer}}

{
  "jsonrpc": "2.0",
  "id": 8,
  "method": "tools/call",
  "params": {
    "name": "CreateEvent",
    "arguments": {
      "subject": "Focus time (self-booked)",
      "attendeeEmails": ["{{anchorMailbox}}"],
      "startDateTime": "2026-06-11T10:00:00",
      "endDateTime":   "2026-06-11T10:30:00",
      "timeZone": "Romance Standard Time",
      "bodyContent": "Self-booked via MCP rest-client test.",
      "bodyContentType": "Text",
      "isOnlineMeeting": true,
      "onlineMeetingProvider": "teamsForBusiness",
      "showAs": "busy",
      "importance": "normal"
    }
  }
}

# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SECTION 4 — WorkIQ Word MCP (agent365)
# Endpoint: https://agent365.svc.cloud.microsoft/agents/tenants/{tenantId}/servers/mcp_WordServer
# Requires a bearer token whose `aud` = agent365 app id (ea9ffc3e-…) and whose
# `scp` includes the Word scope (e.g. `McpServers.Word.All`).
# Tools (preview, may change): CreateDocument, GetDocumentContent,
#                              AddComment, ReplyToComment
# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ─── Word-specific auth variables ────────────────────────────────────────────
# Same shape as Section 3 (Calendar). The middle-tier client must be
# pre-authorized (or admin-consented) for `McpServers.Word.All` on the
# agent365 API (ea9ffc3e-…). If you get AADSTS65001 / invalid_scope, repeat
# the OPTION A registration steps from Section 3 but pick `McpServers.Word.All`
# instead of `McpServers.CalendarTools.All`.

# Resource URL — discovered via 4.6 (RFC 9728 metadata):
@wordResource = https://agent365.svc.cloud.microsoft/agents/tenants/{{tenantId}}/servers/mcp_WordServer
@wordScope    = {{wordResource}}/.default offline_access openid profile
# Fallbacks (only if AAD returns invalid_scope):
#   {{agent365AppId}}/McpServers.Word.All offline_access
#   {{agent365AppId}}/.default

# Paste the access_token from step 4.0b below into this variable.
# Required: aud = ea9ffc3e-…, scp contains a Word scope (McpServers.Word.All).
@wordBearer  = PASTE_WORD_ACCESS_TOKEN_HERE

### 4.0a Start device-code flow for Word scope
# After running, open the returned `verification_uri` and enter `user_code`,
# **consent to the Word scope** on that page.
# @name wordDeviceCode
POST https://login.microsoftonline.com/{{tenantId}}/oauth2/v2.0/devicecode
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded

client_id={{deviceClientId}}&scope={{wordScope}}

### 4.0b Poll for the Word access token (run AFTER 4.0a is complete)
# Auto-uses device_code from 4.0a. Copy `access_token` into @wordBearer above.
# @name wordToken
POST https://login.microsoftonline.com/{{tenantId}}/oauth2/v2.0/token
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded

grant_type=urn:ietf:params:oauth:grant-type:device_code&client_id={{deviceClientId}}&device_code={{wordDeviceCode.response.body.device_code}}

### 4.0c Decode current @wordBearer (sanity check audience + scopes)
# Confirm aud = ea9ffc3e-8a23-4a7d-836d-234d7c7565c1 AND scp contains a Word entry.
# PowerShell one-liner:
#   $t = "<token>"; $p = $t.Split('.')[1].PadRight(($t.Split('.')[1].Length + 3) -band -bnot 3, '='); [Text.Encoding]::UTF8.GetString([Convert]::FromBase64String($p.Replace('-','+').Replace('_','/')))

### 4.1 initialize (REQUIRED first call per MCP spec)
# @name wordInit
POST {{wordMcp}}
Accept: {{accept}}
Content-Type: application/json
MCP-Protocol-Version: {{mcpVersion}}
x-anchor-mailbox: {{anchorMailbox}}
Authorization: Bearer {{wordBearer}}

{
  "jsonrpc": "2.0",
  "id": 1,
  "method": "initialize",
  "params": {
    "protocolVersion": "2025-06-18",
    "capabilities": {},
    "clientInfo": { "name": "rest-client", "version": "0.0.1" }
  }
}

### 4.2 tools/list
POST {{wordMcp}}
Accept: {{accept}}
Content-Type: application/json
MCP-Protocol-Version: {{mcpVersion}}
x-anchor-mailbox: {{anchorMailbox}}
Authorization: Bearer {{wordBearer}}

{ "jsonrpc": "2.0", "id": 2, "method": "tools/list" }

### 4.3 resources/list
POST {{wordMcp}}
Accept: {{accept}}
Content-Type: application/json
MCP-Protocol-Version: {{mcpVersion}}
x-anchor-mailbox: {{anchorMailbox}}
Authorization: Bearer {{wordBearer}}

{ "jsonrpc": "2.0", "id": 3, "method": "resources/list" }

### 4.4 prompts/list
POST {{wordMcp}}
Accept: {{accept}}
Content-Type: application/json
MCP-Protocol-Version: {{mcpVersion}}
x-anchor-mailbox: {{anchorMailbox}}
Authorization: Bearer {{wordBearer}}

{ "jsonrpc": "2.0", "id": 4, "method": "prompts/list" }

### 4.5 401 diagnostic — read the WWW-Authenticate header
# Use this if 4.1 returns 401. Check the response headers for
# `WWW-Authenticate: Bearer error="invalid_token", error_description="..."`
# which states the EXACT reason (bad audience, missing scope, expired, etc.).
OPTIONS {{wordMcp}}
Authorization: Bearer {{wordBearer}}

### 4.6 Discover protected-resource metadata (RFC 9728)
# Tells you the canonical `resource` (= required aud), `scopes_supported`,
# and `authorization_servers`. Update @wordScope to match `scopes_supported[0]`
# (e.g. "<resource>/McpServers.Word.All") and re-run 4.0a → 4.0b.
# @name wordResourceMeta
GET https://agent365.svc.cloud.microsoft/.well-known/oauth-protected-resource/agents/tenants/{{tenantId}}/servers/mcp_WordServer
Accept: application/json

### 4.7 tools/call → CreateDocument
# Creates a Word doc in the root of the signed-in user's OneDrive.
# Notes:
#  - `fileName` is REQUIRED but may be empty → server auto-names it Document_yyyyMMdd_HHmms.docx
#  - `contentInHtml` accepts simple HTML or plain text for the body. All tags / URLs must be valid.
#  - `shareWith` (optional) shares the doc with that email address. Omit if unknown — never fabricate.
#  - The response is the Microsoft Graph DriveItem JSON — capture `driveId`,
#    `id` (= documentId) and `webUrl` from it for later AddComment / ReplyToComment calls.
# @name wordCreateDocument
POST {{wordMcp}}
Accept: {{accept}}
Content-Type: application/json
MCP-Protocol-Version: {{mcpVersion}}
x-anchor-mailbox: {{anchorMailbox}}
Authorization: Bearer {{wordBearer}}

{
  "jsonrpc": "2.0",
  "id": 5,
  "method": "tools/call",
  "params": {
    "name": "CreateDocument",
    "arguments": {
      "fileName": "Probation review — Sarah Martinez (MCP rest-client test).docx",
      "contentInHtml": "<h1>Probation Review — Sarah Martinez</h1><p><strong>Period:</strong> Months 1–3</p><h2>Objectives</h2><ul><li>Ramp up on the codebase</li><li>Ship first feature end-to-end</li></ul><h2>Manager feedback</h2><p>Generated via MCP rest-client test.</p>"
    }
  }
}

### 4.8 tools/call → GetDocumentContent
# Reads a Word document by its SharePoint / OneDrive **sharing URL** (not the
# Graph driveItem URL). Returns filename, size, driveId, documentId, plain-text
# content, and all comments. Replace the `url` below with a real sharing link
# (e.g. the `webUrl` returned by 4.7, or a "Copy link" share from OneDrive).
POST {{wordMcp}}
Accept: {{accept}}
Content-Type: application/json
MCP-Protocol-Version: {{mcpVersion}}
x-anchor-mailbox: {{anchorMailbox}}
Authorization: Bearer {{wordBearer}}

{
  "jsonrpc": "2.0",
  "id": 6,
  "method": "tools/call",
  "params": {
    "name": "GetDocumentContent",
    "arguments": {
      "url": "https://testtesttoltest-my.sharepoint.com/:w:/r/personal/phi-lay_TestTestTOLTest_onmicrosoft_com/Documents/Probation%20review%20%E2%80%94%20Sarah%20Martinez%20%28MCP%20rest-client%20test%29.docx?d=wREPLACE&csf=1&web=1"
    }
  }
}

### 4.9 tools/call → AddComment
# Adds a new comment on a Word document. Replace `driveId` and `documentId`
# with the values returned by 4.7 / 4.8 (they are opaque — copy as-is).
POST {{wordMcp}}
Accept: {{accept}}
Content-Type: application/json
MCP-Protocol-Version: {{mcpVersion}}
x-anchor-mailbox: {{anchorMailbox}}
Authorization: Bearer {{wordBearer}}

{
  "jsonrpc": "2.0",
  "id": 7,
  "method": "tools/call",
  "params": {
    "name": "AddComment",
    "arguments": {
      "driveId": "REPLACE_WITH_DRIVE_ID",
      "documentId": "REPLACE_WITH_DOCUMENT_ID",
      "newComment": "Please tighten the objectives section before the 3-month review."
    }
  }
}

### 4.10 tools/call → ReplyToComment
# Replies to an existing comment. `commentId` comes from the comments[] array
# in the 4.8 response.
POST {{wordMcp}}
Accept: {{accept}}
Content-Type: application/json
MCP-Protocol-Version: {{mcpVersion}}
x-anchor-mailbox: {{anchorMailbox}}
Authorization: Bearer {{wordBearer}}

{
  "jsonrpc": "2.0",
  "id": 8,
  "method": "tools/call",
  "params": {
    "name": "ReplyToComment",
    "arguments": {
      "commentId": "REPLACE_WITH_COMMENT_ID",
      "driveId": "REPLACE_WITH_DRIVE_ID",
      "documentId": "REPLACE_WITH_DOCUMENT_ID",
      "newComment": "Thanks — will revise and re-share."
    }
  }
}

# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SECTION 5 — Local /workiq-word-mcp proxy (probation-tracker MCP server)
# Hits the Express proxy, which validates the Bearer (access_as_user), runs
# the OBO swap to mcp_WordServer, and transparently forwards JSON-RPC / SSE.
# Use the SAME @bearer as Section 1 (access_as_user token), NOT @wordBearer.
# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

### 5.1 Health probe (lists the four endpoints including workiq-word-mcp)
GET http://localhost:3001/

### 5.2 initialize through the local proxy
POST {{localWordMcp}}
Accept: {{accept}}
Content-Type: application/json
MCP-Protocol-Version: {{mcpVersion}}
Authorization: Bearer {{bearer}}

{
  "jsonrpc": "2.0",
  "id": 1,
  "method": "initialize",
  "params": {
    "protocolVersion": "2025-06-18",
    "capabilities": {},
    "clientInfo": { "name": "rest-client", "version": "0.0.1" }
  }
}

### 5.3 tools/list through the local proxy
POST {{localWordMcp}}
Accept: {{accept}}
Content-Type: application/json
MCP-Protocol-Version: {{mcpVersion}}
Authorization: Bearer {{bearer}}

{ "jsonrpc": "2.0", "id": 2, "method": "tools/list" }

### 5.4 tools/call → CreateDocument through the local proxy
POST {{localWordMcp}}
Accept: {{accept}}
Content-Type: application/json
MCP-Protocol-Version: {{mcpVersion}}
Authorization: Bearer {{bearer}}

{
  "jsonrpc": "2.0",
  "id": 3,
  "method": "tools/call",
  "params": {
    "name": "CreateDocument",
    "arguments": {
      "fileName": "",
      "contentInHtml": "<h1>Hello from /workiq-word-mcp</h1><p>Created via the local proxy.</p>"
    }
  }
}

### 5.5 Same flow but through the dev tunnel (what M365 Copilot hits)
POST {{tunnelWordMcp}}
Accept: {{accept}}
Content-Type: application/json
MCP-Protocol-Version: {{mcpVersion}}
Authorization: Bearer {{bearer}}

{ "jsonrpc": "2.0", "id": 1, "method": "tools/list" }